post_text: While we at the Laurel School District and the City of Laurel appreciate the concern Mayor Toby Barker has for the safety of his town, we are electing to not sanitize the Little Brown Jug prior to traveling to Hattiesburg. As you may all know, disinfectant spray and other sanitizers are in short supply. We feel it is prudent to not utilize our supply of sanitizer in such a frivolous manner, as the Jug will remain in the hands of the Laurel Golden Tornadoes. Additionally, the Little Brown Jug is a valued historical artifact and will not be desecrated with corrosive chemicals, which could potentially remove the notations of Laurel’s leading record of wins, and Hattiesburg’s leading record of losses. #RivalryFun #BeGolden

post_text: The Mississippi Department of Education recently announced new members of the Mississippi Teacher Advisory Council, and Laurel High School teacher Rebecca Hooper and Laurel Middle School teacher Rachel Virgess were both selected to serve on the state’s teacher advisory council for the 2020-2021 school year. The purpose of the council is to provide feedback to State Superintendent of Education Dr. Carey on initiatives of the department of education, the Mississippi State Board of Education and the Mississippi State Legislature. Join us in congratulating these two outstanding members of the Tornado team. #BeGolden

post_text:
We have extended the deadline to register for Virtual Only Learning. The deadline is now August 21, 2020. Remember school starts August 24, 2020.

We understand that some parents are uncomfortable sending their children back to the physical school setting, so the Laurel School District is providing a Virtual Learning only option for families who do not wish to participate in the Hybrid Model of attending in person two days and virtual three days. To qualify for Virtual Learning only you must register your child with their school and make that request to the school by completing the Virtual Learning Only Student Request Form available at all school offices in the district.

Please reach out to your child's school if you have any questions. We are looking forward to a great school year.

Laurel High School
August 7 at 5:54 PM ·

Congratulations Laurel High School’s student, Micah Hill, and teacher, Rebecca Hooper, for being selected for the 2020 Aspirations in Computing Awards.

The National Center for Women & Information Technology (NCWIT) named freshman Micah Hill 2020 Aspirations in Computing Award (AiC) Affiliate Winner. Hill submitted an application which consisted of a portfolio of her accomplishments and a letter of endorsement. Hill credits her family and many others with contributing to her success, including Laurel High School’s teacher, Rebecca Hooper, who also received a 2020 AiC Regional Educator Honorable Mention Award. Hooper is a Chemistry teacher and Science Instructional Coach for Laurel School District.

post_text: UPDATES FOR RETURN TO SCHOOL: The Laurel School District Board of Trustees approved the district’s recommendation to move the start of school by two weeks. Teachers will return August 14, 2020 and students will return August 24, 2020. This will allow the district an additional two weeks to complete our COVID-19 preparations, and receive all of the safety supplies that have been ordered. Additionally, the district will provide a virtual only option for pre-kindergarten and kindergarten students. This new season of our lives has created new challenges, but we remain committed to academics and the health of our Tornado family. #LoveLaurel #BeGolden

post_text:
Help us welcome Coach Jones to his new position as head softball coach. Laurel High School Ninth Grade Boys Basketball Coach and Welding Instructor Stan Jones will be joining the Lady Tornadoes Softball Team as head coach.

“I am excited about this opportunity,” Jones said. “I look forward to getting our students ready for the season and building the program.”

Coach Jones has 11 years of experience in education, and has been with the Laurel School District for five years. He attended Jones College on a basketball scholarship where he graduated with an associate’s degree in early childhood education and received his welding certification. He received a Bachelor of Science in physical education from Rust College, where he attended on a baseball scholarship.

“We look forward to seeing Coach Jones grow our girls softball program,” said Laurel School District Athletic Director Ryan Earnest. “Coach Jones has the ability to motivate and inspire and was the perfect choice for the job.” #BeGolden #LoveLaurel

post_text: Firefighters from Laurel and Jones County responded to a fire at the Wisner Building located on the Stewart M. Jones Campus late Saturday, July 4, 2020. The fire was reported to have been started by fireworks. The main school building, home to Laurel Magnet School of the Arts, appears to be safe and unharmed. We are thankful for the dedicated firefighters who worked extremely hard to extinguish the blaze. The Wisner Building was currently being utilized as storage for the district.

post_text: Today is the last day for Grab & Go Meals. Come see us! We are at Oak Park, Laurel Middle and Laurel High until 1 pm!
shared_text:
Laurel School District
May 6 at 1:08 PM ·

Our Grab & Go Meal service is back, but for a limited time. Meals will be given out in a drive through fashion from 11:00 a.m. until 1:00 p.m. on the days listed below.

Monday, May 11
Thursday, May 14
Monday, May 18
Thursday, May 21

On Mondays children will receive three days' worth of breakfasts and lunches and on Thursdays children will receive two days' worth. The Grab & Go meals will be distributed from the Laurel High School and Laurel Middle School car rider lanes, and Oak Park Elementary Bus Loop.

The meals are free to children ages 0-18. Children MUST present to receive a meal and meals are available to any child, even those not enrolled in the Laurel School District. Meals will be given out first come, first served. Limited quantity available. Please do not park and do not exit the vehicle.

Lunches are intended to be eaten immediately or should be stored in the refrigerator within two hours. Please discard any leftovers within 3 days. Hot foods should be kept hot (entrees >135 degrees) and cold foods (milk & cheeses < 41 degrees) kept cold.

Meals will be given out first come, first served. Limited quantity available. Please do not park and do not exit the vehicle.

Lunches are intended to be eaten immediately or should be stored in the refrigerator within two hours. Please discard any leftovers within 3 days. Hot foods should be kept hot (entrees >135 degrees) and cold foods (milk & cheeses < 41 degrees) kept cold.

post_text:
Help us congratulate Oak Park Assistant Principal Shanetra Addae. She will be leading Laurel Upper Elementary School this upcoming school year as supervising principal. #LoveLaurel #BeGolden

Addae began her career in education as a sixth grade math teacher. Prior to coming to Laurel in August 2014, she worked as a sixth grade math teacher and second grade math teacher. While in the Laurel School District she has served as a third grade teacher, instructional facilitator, and is currently an assistant principal at Oak Park Elementary School.

She received a Bachelor of Science in elementary education from Mississippi State University, Master of Arts in curriculum and instruction from Ashford University and specialist degree in educational leadership from Arkansas State University.
Addae will officially begin her service to Laurel Upper Elementary School on July 1, 2020.

“I love being able to inspire and encourage students to reach their highest potential,” Addae said. “I look forward to an amazing school year and to being a part of the success at Laurel Upper Elementary.”

post_text: The Sunday, April 19, 2020 fire that occurred at the Nora Davis Campus is being investigated as arson. Monday’s investigation showed extensive vandalism throughout the campus’ buildings, including busted windows and doors, expelled fire extinguishers, smashed equipment, spilled paint and janitorial supplies, pried doors, broken bathroom mirrors, ripped out wiring, flooded bathrooms, and more. Following the December 2019 EF3 tornado that struck the campus, salvageable items were in storage in the campus’ gymnasium. It appears boxes of books were dumped and set on fire, causing extensive smoke damage to the gym and attached offices. The Laurel Fire Department and Laurel Police Department are in charge of the investigation. Additionally, the state fire marshal will be called in to aid in the investigation. Anyone with information about the case is asked to call the LPD at 601-399-4440 or Crime Stoppers at 601-428-STOP (7867). We are extremely disappointed in these reprehensible actions.

shared_text:
Laurel Leader-Call
April 3 at 11:45 AM ·

As the global pandemic continues, the Laurel Leader-Call will be featuring community heroes who are taking action in the face of world-altering adversity.

Leander Bridges II, director of child nutrition for Laurel Schools, helped put together the district’s ongoing program that provides free meals for families and children in need. He and his teammates will be at Laurel High and Laurel Middle schools every weekday from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. They currently serve about 2,000 meals per day.

“Right before spring break, the superintendent and I began making plans to continue serving our students,” Bridges said. “Our cafeteria ladies chipped in on this big time. The grab-and-go style allows us to maintain social distancing and keep the kids safe.”

Thank you, Leander Bridges II and the Laurel School District. We look forward to recognizing more of our local heroes in the days to come! If you know someone worthy of being "Superhero of the Day," send us a message!

post_text:
HAPPENING NOW: The Laurel School District will begin offering free Grab & Go meals to children 0-18 on Monday, March 23, 2020. The Grab & Go meals will be distributed from the Laurel High School and Laurel Middle School car rider lanes. For Laurel Middle School use the Ferrill Street car rider loop and for Laurel High School enter the parking lot at the 11th Street side and exit on the 12th Street side. Meals will be given out in a drive through fashion Mondays through Fridays from 11:00 a.m. until 1:00 p.m.

The meals are free to children ages 0-18. Children must be physically present to receive a meal and are available to any child, even those not enrolled in the Laurel School District. Meals will be given out first come, first served. Please do not park and do not exit the vehicle.

Each bag will include lunch and breakfast. Lunches are intended to be eaten immediately or should be stored in the refrigerator within two hours. Please discard any leftovers within 3 days. Hot foods should be kept hot (entrees >135 degrees) and cold foods (milk & cheeses < 41 degrees) kept cold.

With today’s news of school closure through April 17, 2020, I know you all have a lot of questions. I assure you that in time, we will have the answers. We ask for your patience with us as we work to develop a plan for moving forward. It’s going to take time, but we are committed to our Tornado family. Tomorrow we will be releasing the details of our Grab-and-Go meal service for children. And next week, we will have more details about continued learning opportunities for our students. This is something we’ve never experienced before, but we are looking forward to rising to the challenge. We will post updates to this Facebook page and www.laurelschools.org/update
#BeGolden #LoveLaurel #LaurelStrong ❤️🌪

He plans to major in sports management. Join us in congratulating Antwan. #BeGolden #LoveLaurel

post_text: Schools in the Laurel School District received recognition at the United Way of the Pine Belt Region’s Annual Meeting and Awards Luncheon for employee contributions made to the 2019 campaign. Oak Park Elementary School was presented the Spirit of Giving Trophy awarded to the Laurel school with the largest percentage increase in giving over the previous year's United Way campaign. The Laurel Education Center and Oak Park Elementary School were each awarded a President’s Award of Excellence for having a 25 percent increase in giving over the previous year’s campaign. The United Way of the Pine Belt Region is the fundraising arm for qualifying human service agencies in five counties in the state of Mississippi. Those counties are Covington, Jasper, Jones, Smith and Wayne. Way to go Tornadoes! #BeGolden #LoveLaurel

The United Way of the Pine Belt Region is the fundraising arm for qualifying human service agencies in five counties in the state of Mississippi. Those counties are Covington, Jasper, Jones, Smith and Wayne. Way to go Tornadoes! #BeGolden #LoveLaurel

shared_text:
Oak Park Elementary School
January 7 at 8:59 PM ·

Hello Oak Park Family!

We are gearing up for our first Parent Academy session of 2020. There are a few things we want you to know:

1. Parent Academy is open to anyone with children (or grandchildren) who will be starting Pre-K or kindergarten within the next year. (Mason & Magnet students are welcome!)

2. All information given is FREE and research-based.

3. We provide childcare, snacks, and door prizes!

4. Childcare workers are able to earn contact hours. (We give you your certificate in hand before you leave.)

5. Each session is specific and includes hands-on resources you can easily use at home or in the classroom.

We are serious about early literacy at Oak Park & we hope you are too! If you know of anyone who would benefit from this wonderful opportunity, please share! See you Thursday @ 5:30 p.m.! (Please park near the gym/swimming pool area.)

post_text: For her outstanding leadership and dedicated service, Laurel Magnet School of the Arts Principal Dr. Kiana Pendleton was selected as the Laurel School District’s Administrator of the Year. Pendleton, along with the work of dedicated students, teachers, staff and parents, moved the school from a B to an A on the 2018-19 state testing results, achieving the highest rating the school has seen on the state’s accountability model in over a decade. Due to her selection as the Laurel School District’s Administrator of the Year, Pendleton’s nomination will be forwarded to the Mississippi Department of Education Administrator of the Year Program for consideration on the state level. Join us in congratulating Laurel School District Administrator of the Year Dr. Pendleton! #LoveLaurel #BeGolden
